Problems

In this exam, you will work with data from three wind farms operated by a company in Norway. The datasets provided contain information about wind turbines, including their unique IDs, locations, models, installation dates, and maximum production capacities. Additionally, you have access to wind speed observations recorded hourly over a three-month period at each wind farm. Your tasks involve loading and summarizing the turbine data, visualizing wind speed data, and creating a function to calculate the power output of turbines based on wind speed and turbine characteristics. You will also perform data manipulation and visualization to summarize power output across different turbines and locations. Finally, you will assess the potential impact of investing in new turbine technologies on power production.

(a) Load and summarise the turbine data.

The .csv file ban400-h24-turbines.csv contains data on all turbines in the data set, with the following variables:

  • turbine_id: Uniqe ID number
  • location: The location where the turbine is situated, one of three options: Bremsund, Kappstad or Kvernes
  • model: The make and model of the turbine
  • installation_date: The first day of operations for the turbine

You also have a small file ban400-h24-models.csv that contains information about the maximum production capacity of each of the turbine models in the turbines data. This table contains two variables:

  • model: The make and model of the turbine
  • capacity: The maximum production capacity of the turbine, in kilowatts (kW)

Load the data into memory, and create a summary table with counts of the number of turbines of each model at each location. The table should also display the maximum production capacity of the turbines.

(b) Load and visualize the wind data.

The file ban400-h24-wind.csv contains hourly observations of mean wind at all three wind farms for the last three months of 2023. This table has three columns:

  • name: The name of the location
  • time: The timestamp of the observation in the format dd.mm.YYYY HH:MM
  • mean_wind: The average wind at the location over the hour that ends at time

Load this data into memory and create one line plot showing the three time series with different colors. Format the plot to make it publication ready.

Hint: Remember to convert the time column to an appropriate variable type using, for example, a conversion function in the lubridate package.

wind <- 
  read_csv(here("data", "ban400-h24-wind.csv")) %>% 
  mutate(time = dmy_hm(time))

wind %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = time, y = mean_wind, colour = name)) +
  ylab("") +
  xlab("") +
  labs(colour = "Location") +
  ggtitle("Mean wind at wind farms") +
  geom_line(alpha = .7) +
  theme_minimal()

(c) Add wind turbine parameters to the data.

A wind turbine creates electric power according to the following rule: When the wind speed \(W\) is less than a cut-in value \(W_{\textrm{cut-in}}\), the turbine does not produce power at all. When the wind speed is between \(W_{\textrm{cut-in}}\) and another value \(W_{\textrm{rated}}\), it produces power roughly proportional to \(W^3\). When the wind speed is between \(W_{\textrm{rated}}\) and \(W_{\textrm{cut-out}}\), the turbine produces power at its rated capacity, and when \(W > W_{\textrm{cut-out}}\) the turbine needs to shut down to prevent damages due to mechanical stress, and the power production becomes zero.

For the turbines in our dataset these parameters are given in the table below.

Add these parameters to the data on turbine models.

models <- 
  models %>% 
  mutate(cut_in = c(4, 4, 3),
         rated = c(13, 11.4, 10.8),
         cut_out = c(25, 25, 25))

(d) Create power function.

We can formulate the output power function of a turbine precisely as follows:

\[\textrm{Output}(W) = \begin{cases} 0 & \textrm{if } W < W_{\textrm{cut-in}} \\ P_{\textrm{rated}} \left(\frac{W - W_{\textrm{cut-in}}}{W_{\textrm{rated}} - W_{\textrm{cut-in}}}\right)^3 & \textrm{if } W_{\textrm{cut-in}} \leq W < W_{\textrm{rated}} \\ P_{\textrm{rated}} & \textrm{if } W_{\textrm{rated}} \leq W < W_{\textrm{cut-out}} \\ 0 & \textrm{if } W \geq W_{\textrm{cut-out}}\end{cases}, \] where \(W\) is the wind speed, \(P_{\textrm{rated}}\) is the maximum power output of the turbine (given as capacity in the turbine model data). The parameters \(W_{\textrm{cut-in}}\), \(W_{\textrm{rated}}\) and \(W_{\textrm{cut-out}}\) are as defined in Table 1.

Write a function that takes in a vector of wind speeds and returns the corresponding vector of output power. The additional parameters \(P_{\textrm{rated}}\), \(W_{\textrm{cut-in}}\), \(W_{\textrm{rated}}\) and \(W_{\textrm{cut-out}}\) can either be given as single numbers (in which case the power output will be calculated for the given set of turbine parameters) or vectors of the same length of the wind speed vector (in which case the power output will be calculated element-wise over the vector of wind speed and the parameter vectors). The function should include tests ensuring that the dimensions of the input conform with each other.

Hint: Use the stop()-function to generate error messages.

output <- function(W, P_rated, W_cutin, W_rated, W_cutout) {
  
  # Check wheter the input parameters are all of length one
  length_one <- 
    (length(P_rated) == 1) & (length(W_cutin) == 1) &
    (length(W_rated) == 1) & (length(W_cutout) == 1)
  
  # Check whether the input parameters are of the same length as W
  equal_length <- 
    (length(P_rated) == length(W)) & (length(W_cutin) == length(W)) &
    (length(W_rated) == length(W)) & (length(W_cutout) == length(W))
  
  # One of these must be true, otherwise generate error
  if(!(length_one | equal_length))
    stop("Turbine parameters must either all be scalars, or all be of the same length as W")
  
  # Initialize a vector of zeros
  ret <- 0 * W
  
  # It is convenient to create vectors out of the turbine parameters if they are 
  # given as just single numbers:
  if(length_one){
    P_rated  <- rep(P_rated,  length(W))
    W_cutin  <- rep(W_cutin,  length(W))
    W_rated  <- rep(W_rated,  length(W))
    W_cutout <- rep(W_cutout, length(W))
  }
  
  # From here we can do a for-loop that would look like this:
  # for(i in 1:length(W)) {
  #   if((W[i] >= W_cutin[i]) & (W[i] < W_rated[i])) {
  #     ret[i] <- (P_rated[i] * ((W[i] - W_cutin[i])/(W_rated[i] - W_cutin[i]))^3)
  #   } else if((W[i] >= W_rated[i]) & (W[i] < W_cutout[i])) {
  #     ret[i] <- P_rated[i]
  #   }
  # }
   
  # It is much more efficient, however, to use vectorized code directly.
  
  # Which position of the vector corresponds to wind speeds between W_cutin and 
  # W_rated? This works the same way with vector or scalar parameters
  where_cutin <- (W >= W_cutin) & (W < W_rated)
  where_rated <- (W >= W_rated) & (W < W_cutout)
  
  ret[where_cutin] <- (P_rated * ((W - W_cutin)/(W_rated - W_cutin))^3)[where_cutin]
  ret[where_rated] <- P_rated[where_rated]
  
  # Return the result
  return(ret)
}

Create a large data frame where you calculate the power for each individual turbine at each hour in the observation period

power_output_df <-

(h) Discuss

The wind farms discussed above are completely fictional, and the wind data are collected from three random weather stations in Norway.

Use the results you have obtained so far, and comment briefly on the following assertion: âWind is everywhere, so the placement of land-based wind farms should be mostly based on convenience: Out-of-sight, out-of-mind.â

# Electricity production from wind is obviously very weather sensitive, and the
# power curves of the turbines indicate that their production varies
# non-linearly with wind. The "Kappsund" location gives barely more than 5 kW
# per turbine on average, and the monthly production varies wildly. The
# "Kvernes" location gives more electricity per turbine, but not as much as the
# turbines at "Bremsund", which, additionally, provides a remarkably stable
# monthly production. Locations like these should be strongly preferred when
# building land-based wind farms if high and stable production are your only
# considerations. (In reality, one must consider other things as well, such as nature
# preservation, proximity to population centers and infrastructure, local
# political processes, etc.).

(i) Investment in new wind turbines.

Assume it is possible to invest in development of new turbines. A new turbine can be based on any of the three models. Development of a new turbine can be directed to improving one of the parameters as specified in the table below:

Which of these options will give the highest increase in power production? Does the answer depend on which location a new turbine will be placed? Answer the question as well as you can. Make any additional assumptions as needed.

# The script below creates a figure that shows the 
# increase in power production for each turbine model at each
# location, for the three different development options, using
# the historical wind data. 
# From the figure, we can note that: 
# 1:  A lower cut-out in will not increase production, as winds are never
#     observed higher than the existing cut-out
# 2:  Higher capacity will increase production with 10%. This is also apparent 
#     from the power function. 
# 3:  A lower cut-in gives a __more than__ 10% increase in production at 
#     Kappstad. For low-wind location, increasing the number of hours of 
#     production might be more important than increasing capacity. 
# The last point is most important for the turbines with the highest cut-in
# rating. 

experiment_data <- 
  models |> mutate(type="As is") |> 
  bind_rows(models |> mutate(
        type="10% higher capacity",
        capacity = capacity * 1.1
      )
  ) |> 
  bind_rows(
    models |> 
      mutate(
        type="10% higher cut out",
        cut_out = cut_out * 1.1
      )
  ) |> 
  bind_rows(
    models |> 
      mutate(
        type="10% lower cut in",
        cut_in = cut_in * 0.9
      )
  ) |> 
  crossing(wind) |> 
  mutate(output = output(mean_wind, capacity, cut_in, rated, cut_out)) |> 
  group_by(name,model,type) |> 
  summarise(mean_output = mean(output)) |> 
  group_by(name, model) |> 
  mutate(
    output_increase_kwh = mean_output - last(mean_output, order_by=type),
    output_increase_percent = mean_output / last(mean_output, order_by=type)-1
  ) |> 
  filter(type != 'As is')
